  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Promotion of access to water in indigenous communities in Murupu, Roraima</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project aims to supply eleven indigenous communities in Roraima, North Brazil with the means to have potable water and equip them with water management techniques. 

Water supply is extremely precarious in eleven indigenous communities in North Brazil; with community water sources from artesian wells showing signs of decreasing water quality, and water borne diseases. With the communities relying on seasonal rivers and small streams for their water for livestock and subsistence farming, the recent floods and droughts have had a negative effect on the communities&#x2019; food security.  

This project therefore has a twofold approach of community capacity strengthening and advocacy work. This involves training on community-based methods to monitor and protect the water quality from wells, and water collection and care techniques, especially for women; and advocacy of the indigenous health authority, SESAI, to repair the artesian wells in the communities, and lobbying of the indigenous affairs agency, FUNAI, to implement public policies to ensure sustainability of water access and resource management.</narrative>
  </description>
